nd dressing rooms were in-between places that have long been overlooked but were actually marked as indisputably modern through their connections with high fashion. Fashioning Spaces engages with and thinks beyond the work of critics Charles Baudelaire and Walter Benjamin to arrive at new readings of the French capital.Examining literature by Zola, Maupassant, Rachilde, and others, as well as paintings, architecture, and the fashionable garments worn by both men and women, Brevik-Zender crafts a compelling and innovative account of how fashion was appropriated as a way of writing about the complexities of modernity in fin-de-siècle Paris.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFashion in literature. 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)xFrance. 0aModernism (Literature)zFrance. 0aPublic spaces in literature. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266980240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442669802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442669802.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles